✅ How does navigation work in the Next.js App Router?
In the Next.js App Router, navigation is built on React Server Components, file‑based routing, and client‑side transitions.
It enables fast, seamless route changes while preserving layouts and reducing unnecessary re‑renders.

🔹 1. File‑Based Routing (Foundation)
Navigation starts with the app/ directory structure.

app/
 ├── page.js         → /
 ├── blog/
 │    └── page.js    → /blog
 ├── blog/[id]/
 │    └── page.js    → /blog/123
``
✅ URLs are derived from folders
✅ No manual route configuration
✅ Nested routes are automatic

🔹 2. <Link> Component (Primary Navigation)
Navigation between pages is done using the Link component from next/link.

import Link from "next/link";
<Link href="/blog">Go to Blog</Link>
What happens internally?
	• Prevents full page reload
	• Performs client‑side navigation
	• Only the route segment that changes is re‑rendered
✅ Faster transitions than traditional navigation

🔹 3. Programmatic Navigation (useRouter)
When navigation needs to happen based on logic (submit, auth, condition), use:

"use client";
import { useRouter } from "next/navigation";
const router = useRouter();
router.push("/dashboard");
``
Common methods:
	• router.push() → navigate forward
	• router.replace() → replace history
	• router.back() → go back
📌 Only available in Client Components, because it depends on browser history.

🔹 4. Partial Rendering & Layout Preservation (Big Difference)
The App Router does partial navigation, not full page swaps.
With layout.js:
	• Layout stays mounted
	• Only the child page.js updates

layout.js (header/sidebar) ✅ stays
page.js (content) 🔄 changes
✅ Sidebar state preserved
✅ Better UX
✅ Faster rendering
This is not possible in Pages Router.

🔹 5. Navigation + Server Components
When navigating:
	• Server Components are re‑rendered on the server
	• Client Components remain interactive
	• Only required data is streamed to the client
✅ Reduced JS ✅ Better performance
This works automatically—no manual control required.

🔹 6. Loading States During Navigation (loading.js)
App Router supports route‑level loading UI.

app/blog/
 ├── loading.js
 └── page.js
While /blog loads:
	• loading.js is shown instantly
	• Page streams in when ready
✅ Improves perceived performance
✅ Works automatically on navigation

🔹 7. Error Handling During Navigation (error.js)

app/blog/
 ├── error.js
 └── page.js
If a navigation causes an error:
	• error.js is rendered
	• Layout remains intact
✅ Better fault isolation
✅ No blank screens

🔹 8. Prefetching (Performance Optimization)
By default:
<Link href="/blog">Blog</Link>
Next.js:
	• Prefetches data in the background
	• Speeds up navigation when user clicks
✅ Happens automatically in viewport
✅ Can be disabled if needed

⚖️ App Router vs Pages Router Navigation
Feature	Pages Router	App Router
Navigation	Client‑side	✅ Client‑side + partial
Layout preservation	❌ No	✅ Yes
Streaming	❌ No	✅ Yes
Loading UI	Manual	✅ Built‑in
Error handling	Global	✅ Route‑level

🧠 Interview‑Ready 30‑Second Answer
	In the Next.js App Router, navigation is handled through file‑based routing using the app directory and client‑side transitions with the Link component or useRouter. Navigation preserves layouts, supports partial rendering, streaming, and built‑in loading and error states. This results in faster transitions, better performance, and a more seamless user experience compared to the Pages Router.

✅ Rule of Thumb (Say This in Interviews)
	Layouts stay, pages change.
	Navigation updates only what’s necessary.

